evaluation.response:
Many people have these types of obsessive behaviors when it comes to their body and food. It's a complex issue and can be closely linked to self esteem and self image.

These behaviors can be harmful and can lead to other issues, such as disordered eating patterns or body dysmorphia. Try to maintain a positive body image and cultivate a healthy relationship with food. Health is not just about physical appearance but also emotional and mental well-being.

While using certain strategies may help you feel more in control, unhelpful behaviors around food take away from the progress you have made. Here are some ways you can begin to heal from these obsessive behaviors and find a healthier way to think about food and your body.&#x20;

Mindful self-compassion can help you be kind to yourself and be more accepting of your body and eating habits.&#x20;

Recovery is possible at any point.&#x20;

Hopefully, you continue to focus on your health. Ask for help from your doctor if these practices continue.

Keep listening to your body and trying different approaches to feel strong and confident. If you notice your body shape or periods becoming unreliable, seek medical healing before results accumulate.

These behaviors can be harmful and dangerous, and should be informed of underlying consequences. Avoiding people and owning this alone can prevent resilience.

Please seek help from a mental health provider or registered dietician who specializes in eating disorders. They will work with you to help you recover and achieve a healthy relationship with your body.&#x20;
